  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_2' aria-label=\" Gurdeep Singh  versus The State of Punjab pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('2','2025','2025_8_690_729','2025INSC957'); ><font size='4'> <strong>GURDEEP SINGH <span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>THE STATE OF PUNJAB </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 8 S.C.R. 690</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 957</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010006122025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : PAMIDIGHANTAM SRI NARASIMHA<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, R MAHADEVAN</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Issue arose whether the order of conviction and sentence of the appellant for the offences u/ss.307, 353, 332, 225, 186, and 120B IPC and s.25 of the Arms Act, 1959 by the courts below was legally sustainable. Headnotes&dagger; Penal Code, 1860 &ndash; ss.307, 353, 332, &ndash; Criminal conspiracy &ndash; Prosecution case that Head Constables-PW 1 and PW 2 escorted undertrial prisoner from one place to another for the court proceedings &ndash; Appellant- Jail official accompanied them, and after court, suggested the constables to return in a private vehicle<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 11-08-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CRIMINAL APPEAL No. 705/2024</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Dismissed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('2','2025','2025_8_690_729','2025INSC957','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' c